\begin_layout Standard
If possible, let its measure be a rational number 
\begin_inset Formula $p/q$
\end_inset

 so that, by Pythagoras' theorem, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{p}{q}\right)^{2}=1^{2}+1^{2}=2,\mbox{ \emph{i.e.}, \ensuremath{p^{2}=2q^{2}.}}\label{eq:irr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 have no common factor, for, such factors, if any, can be canceled to begin
 with.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Firstly we notice that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(2n\right)^{2}=4n^{2},\left(2n+1\right)^{2}=\left(4n^{2}+4n\right)+1
\]

\end_inset

so that the square of an even number is even and that of an odd number is
 odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:irr"

\end_inset

), we see, that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}$
\end_inset

 is an even number.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 itself must be even.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $2n$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is an integer.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore\qquad4n^{2}=2q^{2}\mbox{ or \ensuremath{q^{2}=2n^{2}.}}
\]

\end_inset

Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{2}$
\end_inset

 is also even and so 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is even.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 have a common factor 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 and this conclusion contradicts the hypothesis that they have no common
 factor.
 Thus the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $OP$
\end_inset

 is not a rational number.
 There exists, therefore a point on the number-axis not corresponding to
 any rational number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again , we take a point 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 on the line such that the length 
\begin_inset Formula $OL$
\end_inset

