\begin_layout Subsection
Closed and open intervals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 be two given numbers such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a<b$
\end_inset

.
 Then the set of numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\leq x\leq b$
\end_inset

 is called a closed interval denoted by the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also the set of numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a<x<b$
\end_inset

 is called an open interval denoted by the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
 The number 
\begin_inset Formula $b-a$
\end_inset

 is referred to as the length of 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

 as also of 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Decimal-representation-of"

\end_inset

Decimal representation of real numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 be any given point of the number-axis.
 We now seek to obtain the decimal representation of the number associated
 with the point 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To start with, we suppose that the point 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 lies on the positive side of 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let the points corresponding to integers be marked on the number-axis so
 that the whole axis is divided into intervals of length one each.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, if 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 coincides with a point of division, it corresponds to an integer and we
 need proceed no further.
 In case 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 falls between two points of division, say 
\begin_inset Formula $a,a+1$
\end_inset

, we sub-divide the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,a+1)$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

 equal parts so that the length of each part is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{10}$
\end_inset

 .
 The points of division, now, are,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a,a+\frac{1}{10},a+\frac{2}{10},\ldots,a+\frac{9}{10},a+1.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
coincides with any of these points of division, then it corresponds to a
 rational number
\emph default
.
 In the alternative case, it falls between two points of division, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a+\frac{a_{1}}{10},\: a+\frac{a_{1}+1}{10},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
i.e.,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a.a_{1},\, a.\left(a_{1}+1\right),
\]

\end_inset


\emph default
where, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

, is any one of the integers 
\begin_inset Formula $0,1,2,\ldots,9.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We again sub-divide the interval
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[a+\frac{a_{1}}{10},a+\frac{a_{1}+1}{10},\right]
\]

\end_inset

into 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

 equal parts so that the length of each part is 
\begin_inset Formula $1/10^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The points of division, now, are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a+\frac{a_{1}}{10},a+\frac{a_{1}}{10}+\frac{1}{10^{2}}+a+\frac{a_{1}}{10}+\frac{2}{10^{2}},a+\frac{a_{1}}{10}+\frac{9}{10^{2}},a+\frac{a_{1}+1}{10}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The point P will either coincide with one of the above points of division
 (in which case it corresponds to a rational number) or will lie between
 two points of division say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a+\frac{a_{1}}{10}+\frac{a_{2}}{10^{2}},\, a+\frac{a_{1}}{10}+\frac{a_{2}+1}{10^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\emph on
i.e.,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a.a_{1}a_{2},\, a.a_{1}\left(a_{2}+1\right),
\]

\end_inset


\emph default
where, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

, is any one of the integers 
\begin_inset Formula $0,1,2,\ldots,9.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We again sub-divide this last interval
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[a+\frac{a_{1}}{10}+\frac{a_{2}}{10^{2}},\, a+\frac{a_{1}}{10}+\frac{a_{2}+1}{10^{2}}\right]
\]

\end_inset

 and continue to repeat the process.
 After a number of steps, say 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, the point 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 will either be found to coincide with some point of division (in this case
 it corresponds to a rational number) or lie between two points of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a+\frac{a_{1}}{10}+\frac{a_{2}}{10^{2}}+\cdots+\frac{a_{n}}{10^{n}},\, a+\frac{a_{1}}{10}+\frac{a_{2}}{10^{2}}+\cdots+\frac{a_{n}+1}{10^{n}},
\]

\end_inset


\emph on
i.e.,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a.a_{1}a_{2}\ldots a_{n},\, a.a_{1}a_{n}\ldots\left(a_{n}+1\right),
\]

\end_inset


\emph default
the distance between which is 
\begin_inset Formula $1/10^{n}$
\end_inset

 and which clearly gets smaller and smaller as 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 increases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The process can clearly be continued indefinitely.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The successive intervals in which 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 lies go on shrinking and will clearly close up to the point 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This point 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is then represented by the infinite decimal
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a.a_{1}a_{2}a_{3}\ldots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Conversely
\emph default
, consider any infinite decimal
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a.a_{1}a_{2}a_{3}\ldots
\]

\end_inset

and construct the series of intervals
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[a,a+1\right],\left[a+\frac{a_{1}}{10},a+\frac{a_{1}+1}{10}\right],\left[a+\frac{a_{1}}{10}+\frac{a_{2}}{10^{2}},a+\frac{a_{1}}{10}+\frac{a_{2}+1}{10^{2}}\right],\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each of these intervals lies within the preceding one; their lengths go
 on diminishing and by taking 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 sufficiently large we can make the length as near to zero as we like.
 We thus see that these intervals shrink to a point.
 This fact is related to the intuitively perceived aspect of the continuity
 of a straight line.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus there is one and only one point common to this series of intervals
 and this is the point represented by the decimal
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a.a_{1}a_{2}a_{3}\ldots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining the results of this article with that of Ex.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "recurring"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vpageref
reference "recurring"

\end_inset

, we see that 
\emph on
every decimal, finite or infinite, denotes a number which is rational if
 the decimal is terminating or recurring and irrational in the contrary
 case
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let, now, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 lie on the negative side of 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset


\emph default
.
 Then the number representing it is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-a.a_{1}a_{2}a_{3}\ldots
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a.a_{1}a_{2}a_{3}\ldots
\]

\end_inset

is the number representing the point 
\begin_inset Formula $P'$
\end_inset

 on the positive side of 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $PP'$
\end_inset

 is bisected at 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

