\begin_layout Definition

\emph on
By the modulus of a real number
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, 
\emph on
is meant the number
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $x,-x$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
according as
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
is positive, negative, or zero
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition

\series bold
Notation.
 
\series default
\emph on
The symbol
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x\right|$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
is used to denote the modulus of
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the modulus of a number means the same thing as its 
\emph on
numerical
\emph default
 or 
\emph on
absolute value
\emph default
.
 For example, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left|3\right| & = & 3;\,\left|-3\right|=3;\,\left|0\right|=0;\\
\left|5-7\right| & = & \left|7-5\right|=2.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The modulus of the difference between two numbers is the measure of the
 distance between the corresponding points on the number-axis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Some results involving moduli.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Modulus of a sum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|a+b\right|\leq\left|a\right|+\left|b\right|,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
i.e., the modulus of the sum of two numbers is less than or equal to the sum
 of their moduli.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result is almost self-evident.
 To see this more clearly, we split it up into two cases giving examples
 of each.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Case I
\emph default
.
 
\emph on
Let
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
have the same sign
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case, we clearly have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left|a+b\right| & = & \left|a\right|+\left|b\right|.\\
\mbox{\emph{e.g.,}}\qquad\left|7+3\right| & = & \left|7\right|+\left|3\right|,\\
\mbox{and}\qquad\left|-7-3\right| & = & \left|-7\right|+\left|-3\right|.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Case II
\emph default
.
 
\emph on
Let
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
have the opposite sign
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case, we clearly have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left|a+b\right| & < & \left|a\right|+\left|b\right|.\\
\mbox{\emph{e.g.,}}\qquad4=\left|7-3\right| & < & \left|7\right|+\left|3\right|=10.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Thus in either case, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|a+b\right|\leq\left|a\right|+\left|b\right|.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Modulus of a product.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|ab\right|=\left|a\right|\left|b\right|
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
i.e., the modulus of the product of two numbers is equal to the product of
 their moduli.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mbox{\emph{e.g.,}}\qquad\left|4\cdot3\right| & = & 12=\left|4\right|\cdot\left|3\right|;\\
\left|\left(-4\right)\cdot\left(-3\right)\right| & = & 12=\left|\left(-4\right)\right|\cdot\left|\left(-3\right)\right|;\\
\left|\left(-4\right)\cdot\left(3\right)\right| & = & 12=\left|\left(-4\right)\right|\cdot\left|3\right|.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Modulus inequality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
If
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $,a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
be three numbers such that
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|x-a\right|<l,\label{eq:A}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
then
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(a-l\right)<x<\left(a+l\right)
\]

\end_inset


\emph on
i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 lies between 
\begin_inset Formula $a-l$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a+l$
\end_inset

 or that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
